<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/403578e38582cdf8bccb7bbdf7ee8a91> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Bovenstuk van een processiestandaard ('alam) van brons en koper met bolvormig centrum dat de zon symboliseert. Daaronder een halve maan en aan de top een gestileerde hand. Aan dit bovenstuk wordt een staf bevestigd om de standaard te kunnen meedragen.\r\n\r\nDe herkomst is Zuid-India, mogelijk Tamil Nadu.\r\n\r\n'This processional standard was possibly made in Tamil Nadu in the southernmost part of the Indian subcontinent. It includes a spherical centre that symbolizes the sun, framed below by a crescent moon. Above, five 'fingers' turn the solar sphere intoa stylized hand. This ceremonial hand, known as a khamsa and panj ('five') in Arabic and Persian, respectively, represents the five members of the ahl al-bayt, also known as panj tan ('the five [holy/pure] people'): the Prophet Muhammad, 'Ali, the Prophet's daughter and 'Ali's wife, fatima, and their sons, Hasan and Husayn. It is also known as panja shah or 'royal hand.' Last but not least, the full moon may refer to al-'Abbas, standard bearer to his brother, Husayn, whose hand was severed during the Batle of Karbala.' Christiane Gruber, The Moon: A Voyage Through Time,' The Aga Khan Museum, 2019, 98." .
